"Papadopoulos A.I., Stijepovic M., Linke P.","On the systematic design and selection of optimal working fluids for Organic Rankine Cycles",2010,"Applied Thermal Engineering","30","6-7",,"760","769",,,10.1016/j.applthermaleng.2009.12.006,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76449090380&partnerID=40&md5=962e83d4abb4141314146308c8541464","Department of Mechanical Engineering, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki, 54124, Greece; Chemical and Process Engineering Research Intitute, Centre for Research and Technology-Hellas, Thermi 57001 Thessaloniki, Greece; Chemical Engineering Department, Texas A and M University at Qatar, P.O. Box 23874, Doha, Qatar","Papadopoulos, A.I., Department of Mechanical Engineering, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki, 54124, Greece, Chemical and Process Engineering Research Intitute, Centre for Research and Technology-Hellas, Thermi 57001 Thessaloniki, Greece; Stijepovic, M., Chemical Engineering Department, Texas A and M University at Qatar, P.O. Box 23874, Doha, Qatar; Linke, P., Chemical Engineering Department, Texas A and M University at Qatar, P.O. Box 23874, Doha, Qatar","This work presents the first approach to the systematic design and selection of optimal working fluids for Organic Rankine Cycles (ORCs) based on computer aided molecular design (CAMD) and process optimization techniques. The resulting methodology utilizes group contribution methods in combination with multi-objective optimization technology for the generation of optimum working fluid candidates. Optimum designs of the corresponding ORC processes are then developed for the comprehensive set of molecules obtained at the CAMD stage, in order to identify working fluids that exhibit optimum performance in ORCs with respect to important economic, operating, safety and environmental indicators. The proposed approach is illustrated with a case study in the design of working fluids for a low-temperature ORC system. Particular attention is paid to safety and environmental characteristics such as flammability, toxicity, ozone depletion and global warming potential. The methodology systematically identified both novel and conventional molecular structures that enable optimum ORC process performance.","Environment; Molecular design; Multi-objective optimization; Organic Rankine Cycle; Working fluids","Computer aided molecular design; Environmental characteristic; Environmental indicators; Global warming potential; Group contribution method; Low temperatures; Molecular design; Optimum designs; Optimum performance; Organic Rankine cycles; Ozone depletion; Process optimization; Process performance; Systematic designs; Working fluid; Design; Global warming; Multiobjective optimization; Occupational risks; Ozone; Ozone layer; Rankine cycle; Structural optimization; Fluids",,,,,,"Hung, T.C., Waste heat recovery of organic rankine cycle using dry fluids (2001) Energy Conservation and Management, 42 (5), p. 539; Tchanche, B.F., Papadakis, G., Lambrinos, G., Frangoudakis, A., Fluid selection for a low-temperature solar organic rankine cycle (2009) Applied Thermal Engineering, 29, p. 2468; Maizza, V., Maizza, A., Unconventional working fluids in organic rankine cycles for waste energy recovery systems (2001) Applied Thermal Engineering, 21 (3), p. 381; Hung, T.C., Shai, T.Y., Wang, S.K., A review of organic rankine cycles (ORCs) for the recovery of low-grade waste heat (1997) Energy, 22 (7), p. 661; Angelino, G., Di Paliano, P.C., Multicomponent working fluids for organic rankine cycles (ORCs) (1998) Energy, 23 (6), p. 449; Yamamoto, T., Furuhata, T., Arai, N., Mori, K., Design and testing of organic rankine cycle (2001) Energy, 26 (3), p. 239; Nguyen, V.M., Doherty, P.S., Riffat, S.B., Development of a prototype low-temperature rankine cycle electricity generation system (2001) Applied Thermal Engineering, 21, p. 169; Spindler, K., Chandwalker, K., Hahne, E., Small solar (thermal) water-pumping system (1996